<item>
  <title>Latex Test</title>
  <dc:creator>Archisman Mukherjee</dc:creator>
  <link>https://blog.integrationfest.in/posts/latex-test/index.html</link>
  <description><![CDATA[ 




<p>Test post with latex.</p>
The objective of this section is to study the sum of <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k">th powers of first <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?n"> natural numbers, that is, the sum <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?S_k(n)%20=%201%5Ek%20+%202%5Ek%20+%203%5Ek%20+%20%5Cldots%20+%20(n-1)%5Ek%20+%20n%5Ek">. Clearly, <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?S_k(n)%20-%20S_k(n-1)%20=%20n%5Ek">. So by the method of finite differences, but applied in reverse, we can see that <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?S_k(n)"> must be a <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?(k+1)"> degree polynomial in <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?n">. But what polynomial is it? Sadly, the exact expression for general <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k"> is not very easy to compute, but we will present a general method. For <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k%20=%201"> it is the sum of an AP, so pairing terms from the beginning and end works, but this doesn’t work for general <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k">. Instead, we will use the Binomial Theorem to get that <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?(k+1)"> degree polynomial:<img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?(n+1)%5E%7Bk+1%7D%20-%20n%5E%7Bk+1%7D%20=%20%5Cbinom%7Bk+1%7D%7B1%7Dn%5Ek%20+%20%5Cbinom%7Bk+1%7D%7B2%7Dn%5E%7Bk-1%7D%20+%20%5Cldots%20+%20%5Cbinom%7Bk+1%7D%7Bk+1%7D"><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?n%5E%7Bk+1%7D%20-%20(n-1)%5E%7Bk+1%7D%20=%20%5Cbinom%7Bk+1%7D%7B1%7D(n-1)%5Ek%20+%20%5Cbinom%7Bk+1%7D%7B2%7D(n-1)%5E%7Bk-1%7D%20+%20%5Cldots%20+%20%5Cbinom%7Bk+1%7D%7Bk+1%7D"><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Ccdots"><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cbigoplus%20%5Cqquad%202%5E%7Bk+1%7D%20-%201%5E%7Bk+1%7D%20=%20%5Cbinom%7Bk+1%7D%7B1%7D%20+%20%5Cbinom%7Bk+1%7D%7B2%7D%20+%20%5Cldots%20+%20%5Cbinom%7Bk+1%7D%7Bk+1%7D">
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cimplies%20(n+1)%5E%7Bk+1%7D%20-%201%20=%20%5Cbinom%7Bk+1%7D%7B1%7D%20(1%5Ek%20+%202%5Ek%20+%20%5Cldots%20+%20n%5Ek)%20+%20%5Cbinom%7Bk+1%7D%7B2%7D%20(1%5E%7Bk-1%7D%20+%202%5E%7Bk-1%7D%20+%20%5Cldots%20+%20n%5E%7Bk-1%7D)%20+%20%5Cldots%20+%20%5Cbinom%7Bk+1%7D%7Bk+1%7D%20(1%20+%201%20+%20%5Cldots%20+%201)">Note how this resembles the strong form of induction. The base case <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?S_0(n)%20=%201%20+%201%20+%20%5Cldots%20+%201%20=%20n"> is known, and to find out <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?S_k">, you need to know <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?S_0(n),%20S_1(n)%20%5Cldots%20S_%7Bk-1%7D(n)">. Let us look at some small values of <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k">. For <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k%20=%201">:<img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?(n+1)%5E2%20-%201%20=%202S_1(n)%20+%20S_0(n)%20%5Cimplies%20n%5E2%20+%202n%20=%202S_1%20+%20n%20%5Cimplies%20%5Cboxed%7BS_1%20=%20%5Cfrac%7Bn(n+1)%7D%7B2%7D%7D">exactly what we got from AP. Now, for <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k%20=%202">, (here onwards <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?S_k"> means <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?S_k(n)"> since we are not varying <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?n">):<img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?(n+1)%5E3%20-%201%20=%203S_2%20+%203S_1%20+%20S_0%20%5Cimplies%20n%5E3%20+%203n%5E2%20+%20%5Ccancel%7B3n%7D%20%5Ctext%7B%C2%A0%C2%A0%20%7D%202n%20=%203S_2%20+%203%5Cfrac%7Bn(n+1)%7D%7B2%7D%20+%20%5Ccancel%7Bn%7D%20"><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cimplies%20n(n+1)(n+2)%20-%203%5Cfrac%7Bn(n+1)%7D%7B2%7D%20=%203S_2%20%5Cimplies%20%5Cboxed%7BS_2%20=%20%5Cfrac%7Bn(n+1)(2n+1)%7D%7B6%7D%7D">Note that each of these formulas can be verified by induction very easily.</p>
<p>Suppose we want to find the sum <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?S"> of the AGP <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?(a+(n-1)d)r%5E%7Bn-1%7D">. We write: <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cdisplaystyle%7B1S%20=%20a%20+%20(a+d)r%20+%20(a+2d)r%5E2%20+%20(a+3d)r%5E3+%20%5Cldots%20+%20(a+(n-1)d)r%5E%7Bn-1%7D%7D"> <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cdisplaystyle%7BrS%20=%200%20+%20(a+0)r%20+%20(a+1d)r%5E2%20+%20(a+2d)r%5E3%20+%20%5Cldots%20+%20(a+(n-2)d)r%5E%7Bn-1%7D+%20(a+(n-1)d)r%5En%7D"></p>
<p>Subtracting the two equations like in case of GP, we get: <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?(1-r)S%20=%20a%20-%20(a+(n-1)d)r%5E%7Bn-1%7D%20+%20(dr%20+%20dr%5E2%20+%20dr%5E3%20+%20%5Cldots%20+%20dr%5E%7Bn-1%7D)%20=%20a%20-%20(a+(n-1)d)r%5E%7Bn-1%7D%20+%20dr%5Cfrac%7B(1-r%5E%7Bn-1%7D)%7D%7B1-r%7D">If the coefficients of <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?r%5En"> are in <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k">th order AP, we simply have to repeat this process <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k"> times to bring down the degree of the coefficients to <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?0">, at which point it becomes the usual GP</p>



 ]]></description>
